Sentiment Anlysis of Yelp Reviews¶

In this project, I'll explore restaurant review data available through the Yelp Dataset Challenge. It includes Yelp data for user reviews and business information for 10 metropolitan areas, and this project will choose Cleveland, Pittsburgh, and Charlotte as the examples to explore Yelp's review.

This project is broken into two parts:

Part 1: testing how well sentiment analysis works in Yelp review.¶

Because Yelp reviews include the number of stars given by the user, the Yelp dataset provides a unique opportunity to test how well the sentiment analysis works by comparing the number of stars to the polarity of reviews.

Part 2: analyzing correlations between restaurant reviews and census data¶

I'll explore geographic trends in the restaurant reviews, comparing our sentiment analysis results with user stars geographically. I'll also overlay review stars on maps of household income (using census data).

Background¶

  • Does sentiment analysis work?
  • The Geography of Taste: Using Yelp to Study Urban Culture

1.4 Calculate polarity and subjectivity¶

Using the formatted text column, create a list of textblob.TextBlob() objects and then extract the subjectivity and polarity.

Add two new columns to the review DataFrame: polarity and subjectivity.

In [10]:
import textblob

# create textblob for each formatted_text2
blobs = []
for t in pittsburgh_rw['formatted_text2']:
    # for the column, join the list in to one string, and then calculate textblob
    blobs.append(textblob.TextBlob(' '.join(t)))

'''
similar to
blobs = [textblob.TextBlob(' '.join(t)) for t in pittsburgh_rw['formatted_text'][1:10]]

'''

# get the polarity and subjectivity number, and add as two columns
pittsburgh_rw['polarity'] = [i.sentiment.polarity for i in blobs]
pittsburgh_rw['subjectivity'] = [i.sentiment.subjectivity for i in blobs]

1.6.2 Re-format the data¶

Pass the subset of review data from the previous part to the reshape_data() function defined below. Explore the result of this function, and in one or two sentences, explain the operation performed by reshape_data().

In [14]:
def reshape_data(review_subset):
    """
    Reshape the input dataframe of review data.
    """
    from pandas import Series, merge
    
    X = (review_subset['formatted_text2']
         .apply(Series)
         .stack()
         .reset_index(level=1, drop=True)
         .to_frame('word'))
    
    
    R = review_subset[['polarity', 'stars', 'review_id']]
    
    return merge(R, X, left_index=True, right_index=True).reset_index(drop=True)

shape_sample = reshape_data(sample)

1.6.3 Calculate the average number of stars and polarity for each word¶

Using the result from 1.6.2, group by the "word" column, and calculate the following three quantities:

  1. the size of each group
  2. the average number of user stars for each word
  3. the average polarity for each word

Combine these three results into a single DataFrame object.

In [ ]:
# groupby
size = shape_sample.groupby('word', as_index =False).size()
polarity_mean = shape_sample.groupby('word', as_index =False)['polarity'].mean()
stars_mean = shape_sample.groupby('word', as_index =False)['stars'].mean()

# merge three colume together 
sample_merge = pd.merge(size,polarity_mean)
sample_merge = pd.merge(sample_merge,stars_mean)
sample_merge.set_axis(['word','size','mean_polarity','mean_stars'], axis =1, inplace =True)

2. Correlating restaurant data and household income¶

In this part, we'll use the census API to download household income data and overlay restaurant locations.

2.1 Query the Census API¶

Use the cenpy package to download median household income in the past 12 months by census tract from the 2018 ACS 5-year data set for your county of interest.

I will initialize an API connection and use the .varslike() function to search for the proper keywords

The FIPS codes for the various state/counties are:

  • Pittsburgh
    • PA code: '42'
    • County code: '003' (Allegheny County)
  • Cleveland
    • OH code: '39'
    • County code: '035' (Cuyahoga County)
  • Charlotte
    • NC code: '37'
    • County code: '119' (Mecklenburg County)

# state code, county code
code = [['42','003'],['39','035'],['37','119']]

# extract the census data of three county from dataset
three_df = pd.DataFrame([])
for a in code: 
    data = acs.query(
        # the list of variables desired from the dataset
        cols=variables,
        # represent the smallest geo unit 
        geo_unit="block group:*",
        geo_filter={"state": a[0], 
                    "county": a[1], 
                    "tract": "*"})
    three_df = three_df.append(data)
    
three_sf = pd.DataFrame([])
# extract the geo info of three county 
for a in code:
    # Use SQL to return geometries only three county's info 
    where_clause = f"STATE = {a[0]} AND COUNTY = {a[1]}"
    # Query for block groups
    # layers[10] = census block groups
    three_block_groups = acs.mapservice.layers[10].query(where=where_clause)
    # append three county together
    three_sf = three_sf.append(three_block_groups)
    
# merge sf and df 
three_all = three_sf.merge(
    three_df,
    left_on=["STATE", "COUNTY", "TRACT", "BLKGRP"],
    right_on=["state", "county", "tract", "block group"],
)

three_list_resta = [resta_char, resta_cleve,resta_pitts]

# change three restaurant to sf 
three_list_resta_sf = []
for i in three_list_resta:
    i = i.dropna(subset=['latitude', 'longitude']) 
    
    # set cordinates
    i['Coordinates'] = gpd.points_from_xy(i['longitude'], i['latitude'])
    
    # transform it to geo dataframe
    i = gpd.GeoDataFrame(i, 
                       geometry="Coordinates", 
                       crs="EPSG:4326")
    # change crs to 3857
    i = i.to_crs(epsg=3857)
    three_list_resta_sf.append(i)
